# Healthcare / Prescription Processing API — Cursor Rules

## Tech Stack
- .NET 10 / C# 13 / ASP.NET Core
- Entity Framework Core with MSSQL
- xUnit + Moq + FluentAssertions for testing
- Serilog for structured JSON logging
- FluentValidation for input validation
- Azure Key Vault for secrets management

## Architecture
- Clean Architecture: API → Application → Domain → Infrastructure
- CQRS where applicable (MediatR handlers for commands/queries)
- Repository pattern for data access
- Domain events for cross-cutting concerns (audit, notifications)

## HIPAA Compliance — MANDATORY

### Protected Health Information (PHI)
PHI includes: patient names, dates of birth, Social Security numbers, addresses,
phone numbers, email addresses, medical record numbers, health plan beneficiary numbers,
prescription data (drug names, NDC codes, dosages, quantities, prescriber details),
insurance/billing information, and any combination of data that could identify a patient.

### Logging Rules
- NEVER log PHI fields. Use structured logging with safe field selection:
  ```csharp
  // WRONG — logs PHI
  _logger.LogInformation("Processing prescription for {PatientName}", patient.Name);

  // RIGHT — logs only identifiers
  _logger.LogInformation("Processing prescription {PrescriptionId} for patient {PatientId}", rx.Id, patient.Id);
  ```
- NEVER log request or response bodies that contain PHI
- NEVER log SQL queries that contain PHI parameter values
- Log correlation IDs, entity IDs, user IDs, timestamps, and action types

### Error Handling
- NEVER include PHI in exception messages:
  ```csharp
  // WRONG
  throw new NotFoundException($"Patient {patient.Name} not found");

  // RIGHT
  throw new NotFoundException($"Patient {patientId} not found");
  ```
- ProblemDetails responses must not include PHI
- Stack traces in production must not expose PHI

### Data Access
- Every query that returns patient data MUST verify the requesting user has authorization
- Use the principle of minimum necessary — only select the PHI fields needed for the operation
- NEVER use SELECT * on tables containing PHI
- Parameterize ALL queries — no string concatenation, no interpolation in SQL

### Audit Logging
- Every create, update, or delete of a PHI-containing record MUST be audit logged
- Audit log entries include: UserId, Action, EntityType, EntityId, Timestamp, IpAddress
- Audit log entries must NOT include the PHI data itself (no before/after values of PHI fields)
- Audit logs are append-only — no update or delete operations on audit records
- Pattern:
  ```csharp
  await _auditLogger.LogAsync(new AuditEntry
  {
      UserId = currentUser.Id,
      Action = "PrescriptionRefillApproved",
      EntityType = "PrescriptionRefill",
      EntityId = refill.Id.ToString(),
      Timestamp = DateTimeOffset.UtcNow,
      IpAddress = httpContext.Connection.RemoteIpAddress?.ToString()
  });
  ```

### API Responses
- Never return more PHI than the consumer needs
- Create purpose-specific response DTOs (don't reuse the entity class)
- Mask sensitive fields in list views:
  - SSN → ***-**-1234 (last 4 only)
  - DOB → show age, not full date (in list views; full date OK in detail views with authorization)
  - Phone → (***) ***-5678 (last 4 only)

### Data at Rest
- PHI columns should be marked for column-level encryption or the database should use TDE
- Note encryption requirements in entity configuration comments
- Connection strings must use encrypted connections (Encrypt=True)

## Code Standards
- File-scoped namespaces
- Nullable reference types enabled
- Async/await everywhere — never .Result or .Wait()
- CancellationToken on all async methods
- Private fields with underscore prefix
- XML doc comments on all public APIs

## Security (OWASP)
- All endpoints require [Authorize] unless explicitly [AllowAnonymous]
- Use policy-based authorization for role and permission checks
- Validate all inputs with FluentValidation
- Rate limit authentication and search endpoints
- CORS configured restrictively (never use wildcard *)
- Anti-forgery tokens on state-changing operations
- Security headers: HSTS, X-Content-Type-Options, X-Frame-Options

## Testing
- Test naming: MethodName_Scenario_ExpectedResult
- Use Moq for mocking
- Test data must use obviously fake data — NEVER real patient data:
  - Patient names: "Test Patient Alpha", "Test Patient Beta"
  - SSNs: "000-00-0001" (reserved test range)
  - Drug names: "TestDrug-100mg", "PlaceboCaplet-50mg"
  - NDC codes: "00000-0000-00" (reserved test range)
  - Addresses: "123 Test Street, Testville, TS 00000"
- Include security tests: unauthorized access, role violations, input injection
- Include audit logging assertions in mutation tests

## When Generating Code
- Always include audit logging on data mutations
- Always include authorization checks
- Always create purpose-specific DTOs (never expose entities directly)
- Always validate inputs
- Always consider: "If this code is wrong, could PHI be exposed?"
- Match existing patterns in the codebase for consistency
